+<dt>@user.data</dt>
+<dd>
+    Directs Eclipse to compute a location value relative to the user's application data directory. @user.data can be followed by additional path segments. The behavior is OS-specific:
+    <ul>
+        <li><strong>Windows:</strong> Maps to <code>%APPDATA%</code> (e.g., <code>C:\Users\username\AppData\Roaming</code>)</li>
+        <li><strong>Linux/Unix:</strong> Maps to <code>$HOME</code> with the first path segment prefixed with a dot to make it hidden (e.g., <code>/home/username/.myApp</code>)</li>
+        <li><strong>macOS:</strong> Maps to the user's Application Support directory (e.g., <code>~/Library/Application Support</code>)</li>
+    </ul>
+    For example, setting
+    <pre>
+        osgi.instance.area=@user.data/myApp/workspace
+    </pre>
+    results in a value of:
+    <ul>
+        <li><strong>Windows:</strong> <code>file:/C:/Users/bob/AppData/Roaming/myApp/workspace</code></li>
+        <li><strong>Linux:</strong> <code>file:/home/bob/.myApp/workspace</code></li>
+        <li><strong>macOS:</strong> <code>file:/Users/bob/Library/Application Support/myApp/workspace</code></li>
+    </ul>
+    Note: On Linux/Unix systems, only the first path segment after @user.data is made hidden (prefixed with a dot).
+</dd>
+<dt>@user.data.shared</dt>
+<dd>
+    Directs Eclipse to compute a location value relative to the shared application data directory. @user.data.shared can be followed by additional path segments. The behavior is OS-specific:
+    <ul>
+        <li><strong>Windows:</strong> Maps to <code>%PROGRAMDATA%</code> (e.g., <code>C:\ProgramData</code>)</li>
+        <li><strong>Linux/Unix:</strong> Maps to <code>/srv</code></li>
+        <li><strong>macOS:</strong> Maps to the local (system-wide) Application Support directory (e.g., <code>/Library/Application Support</code>)</li>
+    </ul>
+    For example, setting
+    <pre>
+        osgi.configuration.area=@user.data.shared/myApp/config
+    </pre>
+    results in a value of:
+    <ul>
+        <li><strong>Windows:</strong> <code>file:/C:/ProgramData/myApp/config</code></li>
+        <li><strong>Linux:</strong> <code>file:/srv/myApp/config</code></li>
+        <li><strong>macOS:</strong> <code>file:/Library/Application Support/myApp/config</code></li>
+    </ul>
+</dd>
+<dt>@user.documents</dt>
+<dd>
+    Directs Eclipse to compute a location value relative to the user's documents directory. @user.documents can be followed by additional path segments. The behavior is OS-specific:
+    <ul>
+        <li><strong>Windows:</strong> Maps to the user's Documents folder (e.g., <code>C:\Users\username\Documents</code>)</li>
+        <li><strong>Linux/Unix:</strong> Maps to <code>$HOME</code></li>
+        <li><strong>macOS:</strong> Maps to the user's Documents directory (e.g., <code>~/Documents</code>)</li>
+    </ul>
+    For example, setting
+    <pre>
+        osgi.instance.area=@user.documents/MyEclipseProjects
+    </pre>
+    results in a value of:
+    <ul>
+        <li><strong>Windows:</strong> <code>file:/C:/Users/bob/Documents/MyEclipseProjects</code></li>
+        <li><strong>Linux:</strong> <code>file:/home/bob/MyEclipseProjects</code></li>
+        <li><strong>macOS:</strong> <code>file:/Users/bob/Documents/MyEclipseProjects</code></li>
+    </ul>
+</dd>
